snippet.textDisplay:
For those of you asking about Urdu language and it's history and relation to "Hindi"...here's some facts.

#1. Urdu language is essentially Persian + Hindustani, with heavy influences from Arabic and Turkish.

#2. Urdu is written using the Persian-Urdu alphabet in Nastaliq script.

#3. Urdu is NOT Hindi

#4. Hindi is a bastardisation of Urdu...a form of Sanskritised Urdu developed in 1881 by racist North Indian Hindus.

Urdu has been around since the 1500s and there is a rich literature to support that.
Hindi has only been around since 1880...there is NO Hindi literature before the 1800s whatsoever.

Hindi essentially is proof of North India's racist mentality. In the mid 1800s, when the British had occupied most of the subcontinent and Mughul rule was over, some north Indian racist Hindu leaders wanted to get rid of Persian-Urdu based language called "Urdu" and replace it with a Devanagari based language.

So what they did was take Urdu, replace all the Persian based words with Sanskrit based words and replaced the Nastaliq (Persian-Urdu) script with Devangari.

This is what Hindi is basically...Urdu came before Hindi. Remember that.
